run, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cailly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French:","topographic name for a person living on a patch of pebbly or stony soil, from Old French <i>caillou</i> ‘pebble, stone’, a word of Celtic origin. Compare   Lacaille   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Currier","meanings":["English: occupational name for a person who dressed leather after it was tanned, from Middle English <i>curr(e)iour</i> (Old French <i>conreeur</i> ‘currier’).","Americanized form of French <b>Caillé</b> (see   Caille   3) and <b>Carrière</b> (see   Carriere  )."]},{"name":"Lacaille","meanings":["French:","metonymic occupational name for someone who caught and sold quails, a variant of   Caille   2, with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>.","topographic name for a person living on a patch of pebbly or stony soil, a variant of   Caille   1, with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>; or a habitational name from La Caille, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Lacoy  ."]},{"name":"Caye","meanings":["French (mainly Lorraine): possibly a topographic name from Old French <i>caie</i> ‘sandbank, dike’.","French: nickname from dialect <i>caye</i> ‘sow’.","Possibly also an altered form of French   Caille   or   Caillet   (or of some other like-sounding surname); compare   Caya  ."]},{"name":"Cayer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adelard, Armand, Normand, Jacques, Lucien, Andre, Benoit, Emile, Fernand, Germaine, Jean-Marc, Jean-Marie.","Altered form of French <b>Caillé</b> (see   Caille   3). Compare   Cayea  .","French: from Old French <i>caier</i>, a term denoting a pack of four candles (from Latin <i>quaterni</i>), possibly applied as a metonymic occupational name for a candle merchant."]},{"name":"Caya","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien, Aurore, Cecile, Girard, Jacques, Normand.","Altered form of French <b>Cailla</b>, itself a dialect form of   Caille   2 ‘quail’ (or perhaps an altered form of some other similar surname beginning in <i>Caill-</i>) or a habitational name from a minor place called Cailla. Compare   Cayo  ."]},{"name":"Caillet","meanings":["French:","topographic name for a person living on a patch of pebbly or stony soil, or a habitational name from (Le) Caillet, the name of several places in various parts of France, from a diminutive of   Caille   1.","derivative of   Cail   3 ‘curds’, a metonymic occupational name for a dairy worker."]}]},{"name":"Osbern","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Old English personal name composed of <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>beorn</i> ‘bear, warrior’ (both of Scandinavian origin). As a modern given name it generally represents a transferred use of the surname that was derived from this name during the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Osbourne","meanings":["From a Late Old English personal name composed of <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>beorn</i> ‘bear, warrior’ (both of Scandinavian origin). As a modern given name it generally represents a transferred use of the surname that was derived from this name during the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Osborne","meanings":["From a Late Old English personal name composed of <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>beorn</i> ‘bear, warrior’ (both of Scandinavian origin). As a modern given name it generally represents a transferred use of the surname that was derived from this name during the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":0,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":20,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":30,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":40,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Osbern de Cailly was born about 1066, in Préaux-Bocage, Calvados, Normandy, France, his father, Osbern de Cailly, was 32 and his mother, Mrs Osbern de Cailly, was 27. He had at least 1 son with Marie de Preaux. He died in 1156, in Devon, England, at the age of 91."},"et":{"about 1066–1156":"umbes 1066–1156","1066–1156":"1066–1156","1069–1149":"1069–1149","–1119":"–1119","1035–1107":"1035–1107","1041–Female":"1041–Surnud","before 1066":"enne 1066","1066